ve singular of Old English  <i>swīn</i> ‘swine, pig’ +  <i>hēafod</i> ‘head’, primarily including Swineshead (Lincs, Beds), but perhaps also Swineyard Hall in Rostherne (Cheshire), recorded as  <i>Swinesheued</i> in 1184, and  <i>Swineserd</i> in Saint Martins without Worcester (Worcs)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Dorthea","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of a post-classical Greek name, from <i>dōron</i> ‘gift’ + <i>theos</i> ‘god’ (the same elements as in   Theodora  , but in reverse order). The masculine form <i>Dorotheus</i> was borne by several early Christian saints, the feminine by only two minor ones, but only the girl's name has survived. In modern use in the English-speaking world it represents either a 19th-century Latinization of   Dorothy   or a learned reborrowing."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":14,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Dorthea Swinstead was born in 1245, in Wragby, Lincolnshire, England as the daughter of Henry de Swinstead. She married Sir John Browne II in 1269, in Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1278, in Stamford, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 33, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1245–1278":"1245–1278","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1248–1312":"1248–1312","1276–1318":"1276–1318","1278–1318":"1278–1318","1218–1275":"1218–1275","1259":"1259","1248":"1248","1269":"1269","1312":"1312","1245":"1245","1278":"1278","Abt 1275":"umbes 1275","1276":"1276","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1318":"1318","1218":"1218","Wragby, East